  RAID Arrays
    RAID 0 (Striping) - Min. 2 drives - Splits data across multiple drives for increased performance but provides no fault tolerance.
    RAID 1 (Mirroring) - Min. 2 drives - Copies identical data to multiple drives for redundancy and protection against drive failure.
    RAID 5 (Striping with Parity) - Min. 3 drives - Distributes data and parity across drives, allowing one drive to fail without data loss.
    RAID 6 (Striping with Double Parity) - Min. 4 drives - Similar to RAID 5 but can withstand the failure of any two drives.
    RAID 10 (Striping + Mirroring) - Min. 4 drives (at least 2 mirrored pairs) - Combines RAID 0 performance with RAID 1 redundancy for high speed and fault tolerance.
  
